-- 
Colombia Stocks: Occidente, Nutresa, Fabricato, Ecopetrol

-- B y   B l a k e   S c h m i d t
-- 
2011-05-09T20:44:20Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-09/colombia-stocks-occidente-nutresa-fabricato-ecopetrol.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in Bogota trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 4 p.m. New York time.  The IGBC Index rose 1 percent to 13,977.61 while the Colcap
Index gained 1.1 percent to 1,670.42, their most since April 20.  Banco de Occidente SA (OCCID)  , Colombia’s fifth-biggest
lender, rose 0.9 percent to 34,300 pesos. The Cali-based bank
will sell as much as 190.45 billion pesos ($107 million) worth
of bonds in the local market tomorrow, according to
Ultrabursatiles SA.  The bank will offer securities due 2013 linked to the IBR
interbank rate and inflation-linked bonds due 2013 and 2015,
Ultrabursatiles, which is helping manage the sale, said in a
report today.  Grupo Nutresa SA (NUTRESA CB), Colombia’s biggest food
producer, rose 1.2 percent to 22,660 pesos after Chairman Carlos Enrique Piedrahita said the company plans to sell new shares as
soon as this month to fund acquisitions in the U.S. or Latin
America.  Textile companies rose after President  Juan Manuel Santos 
said on May 7 he expects the U.S. Congress to vote on a free-
trade agreement with Colombia within two months, said  Andres Jimenez , head of international sales at Interbolsa SA.  Enka de Colombia SA (ENKA)  , a Medellin-based synthetic
fibers producer, rose 0.8 percent to 13 pesos.  Textiles Fabricato Tejicondor SA (FABRI)  , Colombia’s
biggest textile maker, gained 2.1 percent to 48.1 pesos.  Oil companies climbed after crude rose above $102 a barrel
in New York, rebounding from the biggest weekly decline since
2008, on signals that the global economic recovery remains
intact.  Ecopetrol SA (ECOPETL)  , Colombia’s largest oil company,
rose 0.4 percent to 3,775 pesos. The state-run company’s stock
gained on oil prices despite Finance Minister Juan Carlos Echeverry’s plan to withdraw a bill in congress to sell up to 10
percent of shares in the company, said Jimenez. The proposal may
be re-sent once procedural problems are fixed, Echeverry told
the daily La Republica.  Pacific Rubiales (PREC CB) rose 1.3 percent to 49,840
pesos.  Canacol Energy Ltd. (CNE)  , the Calgary-based oil
company that operates fields in  South America , rose 1.4 percent
to 2,195 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Blake Schmidt in Bogota at 
